<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900502-0056</DOCNO><DOCID>900502-0056.</DOCID><HL>   Treasury's Mullins,   Waiting to Join Fed,   Sounds Like Old Hand</HL><DATE>05/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><GV>FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- David Mullins hasn't joined the FederalReserve yet, but he already sounds like an old-timer.   Mr. Mullins is the assistant Treasury secretary who isawaiting Senate approval to a seat on the Fed's board ofgovernors. In written answers submitted to the Senate BankingCommittee recently, Mr. Mullins said he would opposeimmediate release of the minutes of Fed meetings. Immediaterelease of the minutes has long been urged by outsiders, butis staunchly opposed by Fed officials, who value theirsecrecy. Mr. Mullins said release of the minutes &quot;may add tovolatility&quot; in the financial markets.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Mullins also said he would oppose legislationrequiring regular audits of the Fed by the Congress's GeneralAccounting Office, saying that would compromise &quot;theindependence of the Fed.&quot;   But Mr. Mullins expressed some disagreement with FedChairman Alan Greenspan on which federal regulator should setmargin, or credit, requirements, for stock-index futures. Mr.Mullins said the Fed may be the appropriate agency; Mr.Greenspan has argued against giving the Fed that power.   The Treasury official indicated little interest in his owndepartment's efforts to intervene in foreign-exchangemarkets, saying: &quot;In my view, intervention in theforeign-exchange markets has never been an especiallyimportant tool of United States monetary policy.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>